description:
Final pass: This was missed because reviewers focused on the empty slot search and eviction, not the slot use.

Root cause: At lines 619-633, peer_add searches for a slot:
  if (slot < 0) {
      slot = peer_find_oldest_locked();
      if (slot < 0) {
          /* Should not happen: table full but no oldest entry found */
          LOG_ERR(...);
          k_mutex_unlock(&rx_mutex);
          return -ENOSPC;
      }
      ...
  }

Then at lines 635-638:
  memcpy(peer_table[slot].eui64, eui64, LICHEN_EUI64_LEN);
  memcpy(peer_table[slot].pubkey, pubkey, LICHEN_L2_PUBKEY_LEN);
  peer_table[slot].last_seen = k_uptime_get();
  peer_table[slot].active = true;

The slot index is used without validating it's within bounds. peer_find_oldest_locked returns -1 on error (handled above) or an index from 0 to CONFIG_LICHEN_LINK_MAX_NEIGHBORS-1.

However, peer_find_oldest_locked at line 440 casts i to int:
  oldest_idx = (int)i;

If CONFIG_LICHEN_LINK_MAX_NEIGHBORS were set to a value larger than INT_MAX (impossible via Kconfig which limits to 64), the cast would overflow.

Actually, Kconfig limits MAX_NEIGHBORS to 64, so slot is always 0-63. No bounds issue.

But wait - the cast at line 607:
  slot = (int)i;

Same pattern. size_t i is cast to int slot. If i >= INT_MAX, slot would be negative or wrong. But i is bounded by CONFIG_LICHEN_LINK_MAX_NEIGHBORS (max 64).

No bug here - Kconfig bounds prevent the issue.
